play an essential role. Yet our knowledge of how philanthropic responses to disasters are motivated, organised and received is fragmented. This book is a step toward curating our existing knowledge in the emerging field of ‘disaster philanthropy’ and to building a robust base for future research, practice and public policy. The authors highlight unknowns and ambiguities, extensions and unexplored spaces, and challenges and paradoxes. Above all, they recognise that philanthropic responses to disasters are complex, conditional and subject to change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Philanthropy & Charity.2bisacsh1 aBaluch, Alina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConway, Megan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDwyer, Graham, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJung, Tobias, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeat, Diana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeat, Diana, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMcGregor-Lowndes, Myles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoran, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPhillips, Susan D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPhillips, Susan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPue, Kristen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRussell, Shona, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aScaife, Wendy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchlegelmilch, Jeffrey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSeibert, Krystian, econtributor.4ctb